reviewerName: Athena Lee Brown "Lady of the Owls"
reviewText: I don't watch to many documentries.  I was suprised I even chose this one to watch.  I think all should watch this doc. as it is so informative and really and eye opener of who really has the control in the US and around the world.  Take some time and watch when you have time to really sit down to listen with out being inturrupted.

reviewText: I really wanted to like this DVD, believe me.  I will not be influenced by all the great reviews here.  This is so boring and amateur.  It's dryly delivered with no emotion.  The story of Oz is lost and clearly only used as a marketing idea.  They did not explain why the movie Oz was written to communicate these ideas but immediately brought me into boring dry facts. The story goes into factual history of unnecessary details.  All the details causes the meaning to be lost in this film.  This guy shouldn't be making film in my opinion.  I don't care what great reviews this has, this guy is amateur and on the level of a college professor who made a film and nothing more.It's hard to cut down something that is responsible and has a much needed message.  This really was poorly delivered on a low budget.  No talent, dryly delivered. I couldn't stand listening or looking at this guy throughout the film.  Don't understand why he thinks he should be delivering the film.  I have no feeling of who or what he's doing in this film. He comes across as a stranger who did not connect with me in the audience.Few people have the attention span for all these UNNECESSARY facts.  Poor film scripting editing.  Convoluted garbage.
summary: Dry Boring Material - Great Idea Poorly Executed

reviewText: There is no bigger scam in the history of humankind than the "fractional reserve privately owned central bank system". I hope someday we will be free of it, and that's exactly what this documentary is about. Nothing would benefit us more than an end to the debt-based banking and monetary system that enslaves most of the people in the world.
summary: God Save Us From the Bankers!

reviewText: One of the best films I've ever seen in content, performance, editing, pacing, and sheer ability to keep my attention and educate me while also achieving entertainment value. This film shares knowledge of importance to every person in the world and reminds us that we have the ability to change things and control the money supply. I am more than grateful to have watched this film and now it's on my top 10 list next to "They Live"...
